<HEADLINE>
<P>
WOMEN'S DAY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In your description of a speech by Raisa Gorbachev, you refer to International 
Women's Day as a Soviet holiday (Part I, March 8). Given that the whole month 
of March is designated National Women's History Month across the U.S., I think 
your readers deserve a clarification about the origin of International Women's 
Day, particularly since the holiday originated in this country. 
</P>
<P>
The holiday, which is observed all over the world, commemorates a March 8, 
1908, march of many thousands of young women and their supporters. Their 
demands were twofold -- women's right to vote, and an end to child labor in the 
sweatshops of New York City's garment district. The march took place in New 
York City. 
</P>
<P>
MARK EPSTEIN 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
