<HEADLINE>
<P>
DIGITAL'S STOCK PLUNGES ON EARNINGS OUTLOOK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Digital Equipment Corp. on Wednesday became the latest technology giant to fall 
victim to lowered earnings estimates as its stock plunged more than $10 a 
share. 
</P>
<P>
The stock closed down $10.625 at $96.375 in consolidated New York Stock 
Exchange trading, a decline of about 10%. It was the most heavily traded issue 
on the Big Board. 
</P>
<P>
Digital's decline came after the Maynard, Mass., computer maker indicated to 
analysts that its order rate in the current quarter was likely to be lower than 
some analysts' expectations. 
</P>
<P>
Despite success in the marketplace, the world's second-biggest computer company 
after IBM has been a serious disappointment to investors. Its stock price is 
half its peak of $199 a share in August, 1987, which was the time of the stock 
market's all-time high. 
</P>
<P>
Digital's fall followed similar drops in recent months by Apple Computer Inc., 
Microsoft Corp. and International Business Machines. 
</P>
<P>
Analysts said there was no single factor accounting for all the reductions in 
earnings estimates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Corporate Earnings; Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
