<HEADLINE>
<P>
JUDGE AWAITS VERDICT ON OSCAR TICKETS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CLAUDIA PUIG 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Call it the Case of the Disappointed Jurist. Or, the Case of the Confusing 
Telephone Calls. Either way, here it is just six days to Oscar, and one of the 
most famous judges in America -- "People's Court" Judge Joseph Wapner -- can't 
seem to get in on the show. 
</P>
<P>
All the retired Superior Court judge -- whose show is the basis of a running 
gag in the front runner "Rain Man" -- wanted, it seems, was some tickets to 
Wednesday's show. But, as is often the case of getting on the A list in 
Hollywood, it's not a case of who you know, but who knows you. 
</P>
<P>
When Oscars show producer Allan Carr was told earlier this week that he had a 
call from a representative of Judge Wapner, Carr, who says he doesn't watch 
much daytime TV, thought he had a legal problem on his hands. 
</P>
<P>
"I asked, 'Why, are one of my couples having matrimonial problems?' I thought 
he wanted to be a consultant in case of a domestic tiff over the weekend," Carr 
said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
But there was some confusion in Carr's office. An assistant to the producer was 
told that Wapner had been so taken by Dustin Hoffman's repeated references to 
him in "Rain Man," that he thought the Oscars might want him around to perform 
in the event. Carr politely declined. 
</P>
<P>
"My case rests on Judge Wapner," Carr said. "It's plain and simple. I don't 
think he's a member of the Screen Actors Guild. I don't think he's been 
nominated for anything." 
</P>
<P>
But Eddy Jo Bernal, a publicist for Wapner's program, said that the judge 
merely wanted tickets to attend the Oscars show -- not be in it. He had 
mentioned it to a Warner Bros. representative at a recent television 
convention. 
</P>
<P>
"Somebody at Warner misinterpreted and went to Carr and asked if he could be on 
the show," Bernal said. "That's not what the judge wanted at all. He's not a 
star, he's a judge. 
</P>
<P>
"He just wanted to be in the audience and he admires Dustin Hoffman's work." 
</P>
<P>
As of Wednesday, Wapner still hadn't made the A list. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Judge Joseph Wapner 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
