<TEXT>
<P>
The House debated legislation to raise the minimum wage, with Democrats who 
long have sought an increase praising President Bush for supporting a raise but 
saying the amount he has suggested is too low. "It is the first positive sign 
of cooperation on this issue that we have seen in eight years between the White 
House and the Congress," said Rep. Austin J. Murphy (D-Pa.), who managed the 
floor debate for the Democrats. "Democrats and Republicans have made an honest 
effort to work out our differences." The Democratic-controlled chamber is 
expected to vote on the measure today. The legislation would raise the minimum 
wage from its current level of $3.35 an hour to $4.65 by 1992, but Murphy plans 
to offer an amendment today scaling back the final target to $4.55. 
