<HEADLINE>
<P>
BONES THOUGHT TIED TO BUNDY KILLING ARE THOSE OF ANIMALS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
CAPITOL REEF NATIONAL PARK, Utah 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Bones thought possibly to be the remains of a 17-year-old victim of serial 
killer Ted Bundy turned out to be those of animals, a sheriff said. 
</P>
<P>
Utah State Crime Laboratory examiners determined that the bones found Friday 
outside Capitol Reef National Park were those of a cow and coyote, Wayne County 
Sheriff Kerry Ekker said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
Bundy was executed on Jan. 24 in Florida. Before he died, he told detectives 
that he had killed eight women in Utah but identified only three of them. One 
was Nancy Wilcox, whom he said he had buried near the park, 200 miles south of 
Salt Lake City. 
</P>
