<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEWSWIRE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Notre Dame tailback Tony Brooks, who faces two misdemeanor charges in a 
hit-and-run accident last month and was suspended from spring practice, has 
withdrawn from the university, school officials said. 
</P>
<P>
Brooks, 19, left voluntarily for personal reasons and returned home to Tulsa, 
Okla., athletic department spokesman John Heisler said. 
</P>
<P>
Coach Lou Holtz said Brooks' future at Notre Dame is uncertain. 
</P>
<P>
Brooks was charged Feb. 26 with leaving the scene of an accident and driving 
with a suspended driver's license. He had already been prohibited from 
extra-curricular activities, including spring practice, for an undisclosed 
infraction of university rules. 
</P>
<P>
"I know that he was looking at certain options and felt this was the best thing 
for him right now," Holtz said. "It wasn't a situation where he came to me for 
advice." 
</P>
</TEXT>
