283 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
MICROWAVE . . .: GUIDELINES FOR SOUFFLE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JEAN ANDERSON and ELAINE HANNA, Anderson and Hanna are nutritionists and 
cookbook authors specializing in microwave cookery. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
There's been plenty of discussion about whether you can -- or cannot -- 
microwave souffles successfully. We say you can, and we've got the recipe to 
prove it. 
</P>
<P>
Microwave souffles may not rise as high as those made the old time way, but 
they will puff about three-fourths of an inch above the rim of the souffle dish 
and won't collapse the instant they come from the oven. 
</P>
<P>
Microwaved souffles don't brown, it's true. But they are exquisitely moist and 
velvety; and with an appropriate sauce, they are superb. For perfect microwave 
souffles, read -- and abide by -- these guidelines: 
</P>
<P>
1. Follow the recipe exactly. Although you can safely substitute one herb for 
another, never change the basic proportions of butter, flour, liquid, egg and 
principal flavoring (cheese, fish, chicken, for example). 
</P>
<P>
2. For a slightly more stable souffle, use evaporated milk in place of light 
cream. 
</P>
<P>
3. To stabilize egg whites and make them climb to greater heights, beat them 
with a bit of cream of tartar. 
</P>
<P>
4. For a more evenly risen, evenly cooked souffle, use an ungreased 
straight-sided, microwave-safe souffle dish in the size specified, never one 
larger or smaller. Also, smooth the surface of the souffle batter lightly; 
peaks will only dry during microwaving. Finally, use a turntable. It eliminates 
the need to rotate the souffle frequently and gives it a professional look. A 
turntable can sometimes speed cooking as much as two to three minutes. 
</P>
<P>
5. For maximum volume, microwave a souffle uncovered. The top will dry faster, 
too -- a definite plus. 
</P>
<P>
6. To allow a souffle to rise slowly and evenly and to keep its edges from 
overcooking before the center is done, microwave on MEDIUM-LOW or DEFROST. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA032389-0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 34723 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
March 23, 1989, Thursday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Food; Part 8; Page 48; Column 1 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
952 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE BUTCHER: GENETICS TENDERIZES TOUGH EYE OF ROUND INTO A DIFFERENT BREED OF 
CUT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MERLE ELLIS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At one time in this country, as recently as 20 years or so, three or four 
breeds of cattle provided us with some of the best beef in the world. 
</P>
<P>
The English breeds, Hereford, Angus and Shorthorn, were the cattle that made us 
a nation of beef eaters. They were small cattle by today's standards, and slow 
to reach marketable weights. But they were giants in providing top-quality meat 
with the rich beefy flavor that comes from a more mature animal. 
</P>
<P>
Today, there are 74 breeds of beef animals registered in the United States, 
many of them giants in size. Some of the new European breeds reach marketable 
weights even before they reach maturity. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Where's the Beef? 
</P>
<P>
They are babies, barely more than veal, when they become meat for tables. As a 
result, they don't have the rich beefy flavor of a more mature animal. In my 
opinion that is why it is getting harder and harder to find a great steak. But, 
at the same time and for the same reason, beef today is leaner and generally 
more tender than the beef of 20 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
In my opinion the cut of beef has gained more as a result of today's beef 
cattle genetics and crossbreeding than the eye-of-round. Once a tough cut that 
required long, slow cooking to make it even much more tender than the sole of a 
boot, it is now a different breed of cut. 
</P>
<P>
The eye-of-round is one of the four muscles of the beef round (the hind leg of 
the beef animal). It is not now, nor has it ever been, one of the most tender 
muscles of the animal, but from today's larger, younger beef cattle, it is far 
more tender than it was from yesterday's more mature animals. Cuts that a 
generation ago required three and four hours of cooking can be done in a third 
of the time or less. 
</P>
<P>
You will often find eye-of-round in the steak section of the supermarket meat 
case cut thin and labeled "breakfast steak" or "sandwich steak," but that's not 
the place to buy it. Go to the roast section and buy an eye-of-round roast. It 
will almost certainly cost you less per pound and you can easily slice your own 
thin steaks for breakfast or sandwiches, although those are not the best uses 
for eye-of-round. Tender though it now is, it is still not really tender enough 
to be fried or grilled with much success. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Family Favorites 
</P>
<P>
The following recipes are family favorites. They have been for years, but they 
have been updated to take into account the new breed of eye-of-round. 
</P>
<P>
Boliche Relleno is a specialty of the house at the Columbia Restaurant in the 
heart of Old Tampa's Latin Quarter. I got the original recipe from Cesar 
Gonzmart, fourth-generation proprietor of the Columbia, more than 10 years ago. 
The recipe has been changed some over the years for two reasons: The first is 
to simplify it a bit; I don't have the staff in my kitchen that Cesar has in 
his. The second is to shorten the cooking time. Today's eye-of-round does not 
need the 3 1/2- to 4-hour cooking time called for in Cesar's 
great-great-greatgrandma's recipe. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
BOLICHE RELLENO 
</P>
<P>
1 (approximately 2-pound ) eye-of-round roast 
</P>
<P>
1 piece Chorizo or smoked sausage approximately 1 inch in diameter and as long 
as eye-of-round 
</P>
<P>
1 teaspoon salt 
</P>
<P>
1 teaspoon black pepper 
</P>
<P>
1 tablespoon paprika 
</P>
<P>
2 strips bacon, diced 
</P>
<P>
1 large onion, chopped 
</P>
<P>
1 large green pepper, chopped 
</P>
<P>
4 cloves garlic, minced 
</P>
<P>
1 teaspoon dried oregano 
</P>
<P>
4 bay leaves 
</P>
<P>
2 cups beef broth 
</P>
<P>
1/4 cup cold water 
</P>
<P>
1 tablespoon flour 
</P>
<P>
Cooked black beans and rice 
</P>
<P>
With blade of long, thin carving knife, pierce hole through length of roast by 
first inserting blade through meat horizontally, then vertically to make cross 
cut. Be careful to keep as much to middle of meat as possible. 
</P>
<P>
Carefully insert sausage into eye-of-round by starting at one end of roast and 
gently pushing sausage into meat, turning from side to side as necessary. 
Combine salt, pepper and paprika and rub mixture well into all sides of meat. 
</P>
<P>
Fry bacon in heavy Dutch oven to render couple tablespoons of fat. Brown 
Boliche well on all sides in hot fat. Lightly saute onion and green pepper in 
same pan. Add garlic, oregano, bay leaves and beef broth. Return roast to pan, 
cover and roast at 325 degrees 45 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
Remove roast from pan. Strain pan juices into saucepan. Mix water and flour, 
stir into pan juices. Cook, stirring, over medium heat until thickened 
slightly. 
</P>
<P>
Slice Boliche into thin slices and spoon sauce over. Serve with black beans and 
rice. Makes 4 to 6 servings. 
</P>
<P>
Note: If time permits, place sausage in freezer for 1 hour to firm before 
inserting into meat. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
LEON'S MAMA'S GRILLADS 
</P>
<P>
1 1/2 to 2 pounds beef eye-of-round 
</P>
<P>
2 teaspoons salt 
</P>
<P>
1 teaspoon black pepper 
</P>
<P>
1/4 teaspoon cayenne pepper 
</P>
<P>
4 to 5 cloves garlic, very finely chopped 
</P>
<P>
Flour 
</P>
<P>
2 tablespoons butter 
</P>
<P>
1 tablespoon oil 
</P>
<P>
1 1/2 cups chopped onions 
</P>
<P>
1/2 cup finely chopped celery 
</P>
<P>
1/2 cup finely chopped green pepper 
</P>
<P>
1 (16-ounce) can tomatoes, chopped 
</P>
<P>
1 1/4 cups beef broth 
</P>
<P>
Cooked grits or rice pilaf 
</P>
<P>
Cut eye-of-round into 1-inch-thick slices. Mix together salt, black and cayenne 
peppers and chopped garlic. Sprinkle spice mix over both sides of beef pieces 
and press in well with fingers. 
</P>
<P>
Coat each piece well on both sides with flour and, with edge of plate or meat 
tenderizer, pound flour well into meat. Each piece should end up about 1/2-inch 
thick. After meat is pounded, dip once again in flour and shake off any excess. 
</P>
<P>
Place butter and oil in heavy Dutch oven and brown grillads on both sides. 
Remove to platter and set aside. Add onions, celery and green pepper to pot and 
cook, stirring, 3 to 4 minutes or until vegetables are tender. Return meat to 
pot, add tomatoes and beef broth. Cover and simmer 30 minutes. Serve with grits 
or rice pilaf. Makes 4 to 6 servings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, The eye of round is much more tender today than ever before. 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
