Photo, Last Rites for Holy BooksAbout 500 worn-out Jewish prayerbooks were 
buried during a ceremony at the Eden Memorial Park WHERE IS THIS?? last week. 
Children and members of Temple Beth Am, 1039 La Cienega Blvd., gathered around 
the site, while Rabbi Harry Silverstein, left, and Howard Pilch, ritual vice 
president of the temple, delivered boxes of holy books to be buried. Jewish 
tradition forbids the books to be thrown away or burned because that would 
desecrate the name of God contained on their pages, said Rabbi Joel Rembaum, 
below, who led the group in prayer. Instead, the books must be kept in a 
storehouse or buried. "The same as human beings are shown respect when they die 
by returning them to the ground, so too a holy book must be shown respect," 
Rembaum said. Rafi Leib, 11, stood atop a mound of dirt to view the burial. 
Afterward, rabbinic intern Amy Wallk bottom left, directed children around the 
site. Also buried were worn-out prayer shawls and other religious objects. 
SANDRA TATUM / Los Angeles Times 
