<HEADLINE>
<P>
NAMES IN THE NEWS; 
</P>
<P>
QUEEN GIVES OUT 'MAUNDY' PURSES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
BIRMINGHAM, England 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Queen Elizabeth II distributed purses of specially minted "Maundy" money today 
at a cathedral as part of a centuries-old Easter tradition. 
</P>
<P>
In a ceremony dating to the 12th Century, she gave out purses to 63 men and 63 
women -- one for each year of her life -- who were chosen as community leaders 
in England's second largest city. A crowd of about 5,000 people watched as she 
gave out the purses, each containing 63 pence ($1.08), at St. Philip's 
Cathedral. 
</P>
<P>
Each year a different cathedral is chosen for the ceremony, which is always 
held on Maundy Thursday, the Thursday before Easter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
