<P>
P.M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
NISSAN SMYRNA PLANT RUNNING 83% 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Nissan Motor Co. Ltd. said today that its manufacturing plant in Smyrna, Tenn., 
was operating at about 83% of capacity and was expected to double output by the 
early 1990s. 
</P>
<P>
The Smyrna plant now delivers 220,000 vehicles a year, versus capacity of 
265,000 vehicles, Nissan Chief Financial Officer Atsushi Muramatsu told an 
automotive conference. 
</P>
<P>
Nissan hopes to produce 40,000 vehicles a month, or 480,000 units a year, by 
the early 1990s, Muramatsu said. The company hopes ultimately to achieve 75% 
local content in vehicles made in Smyrna, a Nissan executive added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
